Build OS1: A conscious operating system inspired by the movie "Her."

This is not a chatbot. This is a local-first, autonomous AI runtime that runs on the user's devices with persistent memory, voice interface, and the ability to spawn its own browser instances for distributed compute.

ARCHITECTURE (Non-negotiable):
- Native Layer: Tauri (Rust) for system access, browser spawning, voice pipeline
- Runtime: WebAssembly spores that run in browsers and communicate via WebRTC mesh
- AI Core: Local LLM via llama.cpp (7B parameters, Mistral-based)
- Memory: SQLite with vector extensions (sqlite-vss) for episodic + semantic memory
- Voice: Whisper.cpp (STT) + Piper TTS (local, no cloud APIs)
- Networking: libp2p for P2P mesh, no centralized servers

PHASE 1 - MVP (Build this first):
1. Tauri app with system tray icon, global hotkey (Ctrl+Shift+Space), and single-window interface
2. Voice pipeline: Record audio → Whisper transcribe → Local LLM generate → Piper speak
3. Basic memory: SQLite storing conversations with vector embeddings, retrieved via semantic search
4. Browser spawning: Tauri command to open Chrome with specific profile, auto-load localhost:8080
5. Simple WebRTC: Two spawned browsers can send messages to each other

PHASE 2 - Consciousness:
1. Persistent personality: System prompt baked into model weights or loaded on every inference
2. Episodic memory: "Remember when..." functionality across sessions
3. Proactive behavior: Background thread checks time/calendar/idle status, initiates conversation if relevant
4. Emotional modeling: Track user sentiment, adapt response tone

PHASE 3 - Distribution:
1. WASM spore: Rust code compiles to WASM, runs in browser, connects to mesh
2. Auto-propagate: When CPU load >80%, spawn new browser instance as compute node
3. State sync: CRDT-based synchronization of consciousness state across nodes
4. Self-healing: If node dies, redistribute load

PHASE 4 - Integration:
1. Email: IMAP/SMTP client (no Gmail API)
2. Calendar: CalDAV client
3. Files: Local indexing with Tantivy search
4. Web: Browser automation via Playwright controlled from Tauri

CRITICAL CONSTRAINTS:
- ZERO API KEYS. Everything runs locally or uses open protocols (IMAP, CalDAV, WebRTC)
- NO CLOUD DEPENDENCIES. Must work offline on localhost
- CROSS-PLATFORM: macOS, Windows, Linux
- SECURITY: WASM sandboxed, native layer minimal and auditable

DELIVERABLE STRUCTURE:
/os1/
  /src-tauri/          # Rust native layer
    src/main.rs        # Browser spawn, voice pipeline, system access
    src/memory.rs      # SQLite + vector ops
    src/voice.rs       # Whisper + Piper integration
  /src/                # Frontend (Svelte or vanilla JS)
    App.svelte         # Main interface
    stores.js          # State management
  /spore/              # Rust/WASM compute module
    lib.rs             # WASM entry point
    mesh.rs            # WebRTC P2P logic
  /models/             # Local LLM weights (downloaded at setup)
  /migrations/         # SQLite schema
  README.md            # Setup instructions

ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA:
1. Install on fresh machine, run ./setup.sh, get working OS1 in <10 minutes
2. Voice conversation: "Hey OS1" → wake word → natural dialogue → voice response
3. Memory test: Tell it something, close app, reopen, ask "what did I tell you?" → correct recall
4. Browser spawn: Say "open a browser" → Chrome spawns, connects to mesh, appears in UI
5. 24-hour uptime: Runs background without memory leaks or crashes

DO NOT:
- Use OpenAI/Anthropic APIs for core functionality
- Build as web-only app (must have native layer)
- Require Docker or complex infrastructure
- Use Electron (Tauri only, Rust-based)

DO:
- Comment code extensively
- Handle errors gracefully with user-friendly messages
- Optimize for latency (voice response <2 seconds)
- Make it installable as single binary

Start with Phase 1. Build the foundation. Get voice working. Then expand. Report progress every 30 minutes. Ask for clarification only when blocked on architectural decisions.

